ntCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/D002761/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This proposal builds on a body of research that has been underway for more than a decade.&amp;nbsp;The overarching theme of the research is to understand the implications of models of government behaviour for the proper role of government in the economy. The research has two main components:&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>(1) Incentives and accountability in public organisations.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>This will result in a monograph that brings together research on these issues and applies them to the study of public service reform.&amp;nbsp;The approach will build on the motivated agents framework developed jointly with Maitreesh Ghatak.&amp;nbsp;This sees organisations as a vehicle for formulating and developing effective missions with agents being matched to enhance organisational quality. The work will also locate this framework in broader traditional debates in public economics.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>(2)&amp;nbsp;The&amp;nbsp;institutional possibility frontier and the political economy of development.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>It is now widely agreed that good institutions have a key role to play in shaping effective development.&amp;nbsp;This work will develop a number of aspects of this trying to understand the role of political institutions in shaping effective states and providing a foundation for effective markets.&amp;nbsp;This will include improved understanding of the political economy of property rights and taxable capacity.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>243403</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>C7267995-04FA-4C2C-B38A-3E4DF7919574</gtr:id><gtr:title>FRAGILE STATES AND DEVELOPMENT POLICY</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of the European Economic Association</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/69c8b1e727acf1941085502744762952"><gtr:id>69c8b1e727acf1941085502744762952</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Besley T</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfa5fa522e7c95</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>333C1552-492D-4276-92E6-65428CA1B235</gtr:id><gtr:title>Handbook of Development Economics: Volume 5</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/1b723701444a4a4bf